9 FLOOR SUBSTITUTE
10 An Act relating to substance abuse services; defining
terms; authorizing the possession, acquisition,
11 distribution, and administration of emergency opioid
antagonists by any person; providing criminal and
12 civil immunities; providing for codification;
providing an effective date; and declaring an
13 emergency.
14
15
16 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
17 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
18 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 2-403 of Title 43A, unless there
19 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
20 A. As used in this section:
21 1. “Emergency opioid antagonist” means a drug including, but
22 not limited to, naloxone that blocks the effects of opioids and that
23 is approved by the United States Food and Drug Administration for
24 the treatment of an opioid overdose; and
Req. No. 3815 Page 1

1 2. “Person” means, unless the context otherwise requires, any
2 individual, partnership, association, corporation, limited liability
3 company, governmental entity, tribal entity, public or private
4 institution of postsecondary education, or other legal entity.
5 B. Notwithstanding any provision of law to the contrary, any
6 person may:
7 1. Possess and store emergency opioid antagonists;
8 2. Acquire emergency opioid antagonists by purchase or
9 donation;
10 3. Distribute or make emergency opioid antagonists available to
11 any person to the extent permitted under applicable federal law; and
12 4. Administer an emergency opioid antagonist to any person who
13 the person believes, in good faith, is experiencing an opioid
14 overdose.
15 C. A person shall not be subject to criminal prosecution for
16 possessing, storing, acquiring, distributing, making available, or
17 administering emergency opioid antagonists pursuant to this section.
18 D. Any person who, in good faith, distributes, makes available,
19 or administers emergency opioid antagonists pursuant to this section
20 shall not be liable for any civil damages as a result of any acts or
21 omissions by such person, except for acts or omissions constituting
22 gross negligence or willful or wanton wrongs in distributing, making
23 available, or administering emergency opioid antagonists.
24 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective July 1, 2026.
Req. No. 3815 Page 2

1 SECTION 3. It being immediately necessary for the preservation
2 of the public peace, health or safety, an emergency is hereby
3 declared to exist, by reason whereof this act shall take effect and
4 be in full force from and after its passage and approval.
